Here the young poet failed to act up to his Stoic trainingl: under the sear of death his constancy gave way, and after holding out for a while he charged his own mother Acilia with a share in the plot. But neither this nor a string of confessions2 which followed could save him: he was soon like the rest condemned to die, the mode of death being left to his own choice. Accordingly he nerved himself for his end, went into a hot bath and had his veins openedss: there he calmly bled to death in the same way as many other Romans of mark did in those days of tyranny when suicide was the only refuge from despair. While the life—blood ran from him he is said to have repeated aloud some appropriate lines from his own great poem (IX. 811—814):

sanguis erant lacrimae: quaecunque foramina novit humor, ab his largus manat cruor: ora redundant et patulae nares: sudor rubet: omnia plenis membra fluunt venis: totum est pro vulnere corpus.

Thus died Lucan3 and his uncle Seneca and his father Melpst were involved in the same ruin. His wife, the beautiful and virtuous Polla Argentaria5 to whom he had been tenderly attached, survived him many years : and to her were addressed in rnemory of her husband some short epigrams of Martiah and the long and over—drawn panegyric of Statius.

Viewing the events of Lucan's life as a whole we may fairly point to the life of Naevius as in many respects parallel.
